dical Failure -- t12 / Breast Cancer Risk as Disease Biomedicalizing Risk -- t13 / Biopsychiatry and the Informatics of Diagnosis Governing Mentalities -- tEpilogue / Thoughts on Biomedicalization in Its Transnational Travels -- tReferences -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe rise of Western scientific medicine fully established the medical sector of the U.S. political economy by the end of the Second World War, the first "social transformation of American medicine." Then, in an ongoing process called medicalization, the jurisdiction of medicine began expanding, redefining certain areas once deemed moral, social, or legal problems (such as alcoholism, drug addiction, and obesity) as medical problems. The editors of this important collection argue that since the mid-1980s, dramatic, and especially technoscientific, changes in the constitution, organization, and practices of contemporary biomedicine have coalesced into biomedicalization, the second major transformation of American medicine. This volume offers in-depth analyses and case studies along with the groundbreaking essay in which the editors first elaborated their theory of biomedicalization.Contributors. Natalie Boero, Adele E. Clarke, Jennifer R. Fishman, Jennifer Ruth Fosket, Kelly Joyce, Jonathan Kahn, Laura Mamo, Jackie Orr, Elianne Riska, Janet K. Shim, Sara Shostak  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aBiotechnologyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMedical innovationsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMedical technologyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aClarke, Adele E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFishman, Jennifer R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/v